Title: PATTERN-GENERATOR-DRIVEN DEVELOPMENT IN SELF-ORGANIZING MODELS  
Author: James A. Bednar and Risto Miikkulainen 
Address: Austin, TX 78712  
Affiliation: Department of Computer Sciences The University of Texas at Austin  
Note: To appear in Computational Neuroscience: Trends in Research, 1998, James M. Bower, ed., Plenum: New York, 1998.  
Abstract: Self-organizing models develop realistic cortical structures when given approximations of the visual environment as input. Recently it has been proposed that internally generated input patterns, such as those found in the developing retina and in PGO waves during REM sleep, may have the same effect. Internal pattern generators would constitute an efficient way to specify, develop, and maintain functionally appropriate perceptual organization. They may help express complex structures from minimal genetic information, and retain this genetic structure within a highly plastic system. Simulations with the RF-LISSOM orientation map model indicate that such preorganization is possible, providing a computational framework for examining how genetic influences interact with visual experience. 
